data.title: Clark Haggans: Player News
data.meta_description: Get all the most recent Clark Haggans player news, headlines, injury updates, transactions, and more on NBC Sports.
data.text:
Steelers LB Clark Haggans is out indefinitely with a broken hand.

Haggans hurt the hand while lifting weights. He’s expected to miss several weeks of training camp. Signed to a contract extension in the offseason, Haggans was expected to replace Jason Gildon at OLB. Alonzo Jackson will fill in for now.

Related

Clark Haggans

Steelers LB Clark Haggans, out with a broken hand, hopes to return to practice this week.

He thinks he could play by this weekend. If so, Haggans is well ahead of his recovery schedule. He’ll be Pittsburgh’s starting OLB this season.

Related

Clark Haggans

The Cardinals are expected to re-sign free agents DE Vonnie Holiday and LB Clark Haggans at some point in the next month.

GM Rod Graves has already acknowledged that the veterans would likely be brought back. Holliday would play a reserve role behind Calais Campbell and Darnell Dockett. Although Haggans was a 16-game starter a year ago, he’s in line for a backup job with Sam Acho and O’Brien Schofield taking over on the outside.

Cardinals OLB Clark Haggans is currently serving jail time in Arizona for a 2011 DUI arrest.

Unbeknownst at the time, Haggans was convicted of DUI on April 21, 2011. He eventually pleaded guilty to “extreme DUI” and was sentenced to nine days behind bars in addition to 36 days of home detentions. Because Haggans was convicted, he could be subject to a short suspension. It’s not a given, of course.

Related

Clark Haggans

Cardinals OLB Clark Haggans said he’s unsure if he’ll face league discipline stemming from his 2011 DUI.

The incident occurred during the lockout, which might put Haggans in the clear. He did serve jail time in Pennsylvania this summer after pleading guilty to “extreme DUI.” Haggans projects as the Cardinals’ primary backup behind Sam Acho and O’Brien Schofield at outside linebacker.

Related

Clark Haggans

49ers signed OLB Clark Haggans, formerly of the Cardinals.

Per the Sacramento Bee’s Matt Barrows, Haggans is facing a possible three-game suspension, likely stemming from his 2011 DUI. If discipline is handed down promptly, Haggans could open the year on San Francisco’s reserve-suspended list, and not cost the team a roster spot. Though Haggans’ pass-rush ability has evaporated at age 35, he can still set the edge in run defense.
